Lesson 4

Scatterplots

Notes: Use a scatterplot to examine the relationship between two continuous variables.

Load the data and plot with qplot.

library(ggplot2)
pf = read.csv('pseudo_facebook.tsv', sep='\t')
qplot(x=age, y=friend_count, data=pf)

Lets plot the same thing with ggplot.

ggplot Syntax

Notes:

ggplot(aes(x=age, y=friend_count), data = pf) +
  geom_point()

summary(pf$age)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   13.00   20.00   28.00   37.28   50.00  113.00
ggplot(aes(x=age, y=friend_count), data = pf) +
  geom_point() + 
  xlim(13, 90)
## Warning in loop_apply(n, do.ply): Removed 4906 rows containing missing
## values (geom_point).

Overplotting

Notes: Set the alpha parameter to avoid overplotting or geom_jitter.

ggplot(aes(x=age, y=friend_count), data = pf) +
  geom_point(alpha=1/20) + 
  xlim(13, 90)
## Warning in loop_apply(n, do.ply): Removed 4906 rows containing missing
## values (geom_point).

ggplot(aes(x=age, y=friend_count), data = pf) +
  geom_jitter(alpha=1/20) + 
  xlim(13, 90)
## Warning in loop_apply(n, do.ply): Removed 5192 rows containing missing
## values (geom_point).

What do you notice in the plot?

Response: The graph is significantly more consistent now. It is easier to see that most teenagers have fewer than 500 friends and that people over 45 have around 250 friends. It would be better to zoom in on the below 2000 friends region so that the differences are more recognizable by age group. Also, the x axis should have more ages listed. ***

Conditional Means

Notes:

#install.packages('dplyr')
library(dplyr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## 
## The following object is masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter
## 
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
age_groups = group_by(pf, age)
pf.fc_by_age = summarise(age_groups,
          friend_count_mean = mean(friend_count),
          friend_count_median = median(friend_count),
          n = n())

head(pf.fc_by_age)

# to reverse the order
# pf.fc_by_age = arrange(pf.fc_by_age, age)

# Alternate Terminology:
pf.fc_by_age = pf %>%
  group_by(age) %>%
  summarise(friend_count_mean = mean(friend_count),
            friend_count_median = median(friend_count),
            n = n())

Create your plot!

ggplot(aes(x=age, y=friend_count_mean), data = pf.fc_by_age) +
  geom_line() + 
  xlim(13, 90)

Overlaying Summaries with Raw Data

Notes:

ggplot(aes(x=age, y=friend_count), data=pf) +
  xlim(13,90) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.05, 
             position = position_jitter(h=0),
             color = 'orange') +
  coord_trans(y="sqrt") +
  geom_line(stat='summary', fun.y=mean) +
  geom_line(stat='summary', fun.y= quantile, probs = .1,
            linetype=2, color='blue') +
  geom_line(stat='summary', fun.y=quantile, probs = .9,
            linetype=2, color='blue') +
  geom_line(stat='summary', fun.y=quantile, probs = .5,
            color='blue')

# Zoom in with a coord_cartesian layer.
ggplot(aes(x=age, y=friend_count), data=pf) +
  coord_cartesian(xlim=c(13,70), ylim=c(0,1000)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.05, 
             position = position_jitter(h=0),
             color = 'orange') +
  geom_line(stat='summary', fun.y=mean) +
  geom_line(stat='summary', fun.y= quantile, probs = .1,
            linetype=2, color='blue') +
  geom_line(stat='summary', fun.y=quantile, probs = .9,
            linetype=2, color='blue') +
  geom_line(stat='summary', fun.y=quantile, probs = .5,
            color='blue')

What are some of your observations of the plot?

Response: It is very rare to have more than 1000 friends even for younger users. ***

Correlation

Notes: Correlation > 0.3 or < -0.3 is meaningful, but small. Correlation > 0.5 or < -0.5 is moderate. Correlation > 0.7 or < -0.7 is large.

cor(pf$age, pf$friend_count)
## [1] -0.02740737
cor.test(pf$age, pf$friend_count, method = 'pearson')
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  pf$age and pf$friend_count
## t = -8.6268, df = 99001, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.03363072 -0.02118189
## sample estimates:
##         cor 
## -0.02740737
with(pf, cor.test(age, friend_count, method = 'pearson'))

Whats the correlation between age and friend count? Round to three decimal places. Response: -0.027 ***

Strong Correlations

Notes: The correlation coefficient is invariant under a linear transformation of either X or Y, and the slope of the regression line when both X and Y have been transformed to z-scores is the correlation coefficient.

Its important to note that we may not always be interested in the bulk of the data. Sometimes, the outliers ARE of interest, and its important that we understand their values and why they appear in the data set.

Whats the correlation betwen the two variables? Include the top 5% of values for the variable in the calculation and round to 3 decimal places.

cor.test(pf$www_likes_received, pf$likes_received, method = 'pearson')
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation

Understanding Noise: Age to Age Months

Notes:

ggplot(aes(x=age, y=friend_count_mean), data = subset(pf.fc_by_age, age < 71)) +
  geom_line()

Age with Months Means

pf$age_with_months = pf$age + (12 - pf$dob_month) / 12

pf.fc_by_age_months = pf %>%
  group_by(age_with_months) %>%
  summarise(friend_count_mean = mean(friend_count),
            friend_count_median = median(friend_count),
            n = n())

head(pf.fc_by_age_months)
## Source: local data frame [6 x 4]
## 
##   age_with_months friend_count_mean friend_count_median  n
## 1        13.16667          46.33333                30.5  6
## 2        13.25000         115.07143                23.5 14
## 3        13.33333         136.20000                44.0 25
## 4        13.41667         164.24242                72.0 33
## 5        13.50000         131.17778                66.0 45
## 6        13.58333         156.81481                64.0 54
ggplot(aes(x=age_with_months, y=friend_count_mean), data = subset(pf.fc_by_age_months, age_with_months < 71)) +
  geom_line()

Smoothing Conditional Means

Notes: Smoothing can allow to see bigger trends in data, but it also obscures a lot of detail. This is an example of the bias/variance tradeoff.

p1 = ggplot(aes(x=age, y=friend_count_mean), data = subset(pf.fc_by_age, age < 71)) +
  geom_line() + 
  geom_smooth()

p2 = ggplot(aes(x=age_with_months, y=friend_count_mean), data = subset(pf.fc_by_age_months, age_with_months < 71)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_smooth()

p3 = ggplot(aes(x = round(age/5) * 5, y = friend_count),
            data = subset(pf, age < 71)) +
  geom_line(stat = 'summary', fun.y=mean)

library(gridExtra)
## Loading required package: grid
grid.arrange(p2, p1, p3, ncol= 1)
